As Flannery O'Connor says, “A story is a way to say something that can't be said any other way... you tell a story because a statement would be inadequate.” No matter how thoroughly we describe the features of a literary work, something transcendent remains. I believe ethics shares this characteristic. As Wittgenstein puts it, “It is clear that ethics cannot be expressed. / Ethics is transcendental.” I suggest that this “something”, this je ne sais quoi, is the most powerful attribute of art and morality, and that the transcendental nature of both ethics and aesthetics provides a connection between them.

I believe morality and art are closely related because we experience both most powerfully at a noumenal level, to use a Kantian term. They affect us in a way that can be experienced but not fully explained. This link is even stronger with the art of literature. As McKean states, “What most distinguishes literature from the other arts, what is, in truth, unique about the art, is its moral quality. Moral standards may be unsuitable for other arts, like music, but they seem as relevant to literature as they are to life itself. Living necessarily involves values... Literature is important to us precisely because of the values we find there.”

Today's Germany is seen as a formidable power, a united nation with its own unique culture extending from the Alps' shadows in Munich to the Baltic Sea city of Kiel. This same culture is felt from Cologne on the Rhine, through Germany's center to the Saxon city of Dresden on the Elbe. Given such a distinctive culture, it's no wonder that modern Germany originates from multiple sources and tribes.

Germania is the ancestral homeland of the Germans. The name's origins are hotly contested among scholars and historians. Tacitus claimed it came from a Germanic tribe called the Tungrians, previously known as Germans before they crossed the Rhine and clashed with Gaulish forces (Tacitus, 98). Julius Caesar first used "Germanus" in his Gallic Wars commentary, describing how he subdued the Gauls and fought Germanic tribes crossing the Rhine under deceptive pretenses. He adopted this term from the Gauls to distinguish between those he had conquered (the Gauls) and those he hadn't. Though the origin remains uncertain, some suggest it referred to a neighboring term in the Gaulish language. In the first chapter of his first book on these wars, Julius Caesar notes, "Germans, who dwell beyond the Rhine, with whom they (the Gauls) are continuously waging war... They contend with the Germans in nearly daily battles" (Julius Caesar, 50-40 BC). Others argue the name derives from the spear they used in warfare, known as a ger (O.E.D, 2010), or perhaps from the Old Irish word garim, meaning "to shout," suggesting the Germans were loud or noisy (Names of Germany).

The early Roman historian Tacitus wrote in his AD 98 work "De Origine et situ Germanorum," discussing the Germans' origins, "I should regard (the Germans) as aboriginal, not mixed with other races through immigration or intercourse. For, in former times, it was not by land but on shipboard that those who sought to emigrate would arrive... Who would leave Asia or Africa for Italy for Germany, with its wild country, its harsh skies, its grim manners and appearance, unless indeed it were his home?" (Tacitus, 98).

And who would leave Rome for Germania? Certainly not the Romans, not yet anyway. They sent expeditions into Germania for goods and led occasional land campaigns, but mostly returned to their expansive empire. As the Germanic tribes emerged in the mid-first century, they lived at the Roman Empire's borders, trading goods from the land and their skills by serving in the Roman army ranks (Ozment, 2005, pg. 17).

The play "Twelfth Night" suggests that while disguise can be effective in maintaining prolonged deception, ultimately, a person must discard this newly assumed identity, or risk losing themselves entirely in the process. A major challenge in ending a deception is the potential for feeling alienated. Therefore, one must choose between self-preservation and maintaining relationships with others. Although some may react neutrally upon realizing they've been deceived, others might not take it so lightly and could be offended by the entire charade.

Deception involving gender role reversal is particularly complex, as it raises numerous questions, the most pressing being why? Why does someone feel compelled to abandon their identity and assume a disguise of the opposite gender? For Viola, it is clearly a means of self-protection: "I'll bring you to a captain in this town, where my maiden garments lie, through whose gentle aid I was preserved to serve this noble count..." (5.1.247-249)

Newly arrived in a foreign land, Viola feels the need to pose as a man for protection against potential threats. Her plan is successful but alienates her from the women around her, cutting her off from crucial support. To complicate matters, she is so convincing in her male guise that Olivia confuses her with Sebastian and falls in love with her. "Where to, my lord? Cesario, husband, stay." (5.1.138) Additionally, she must navigate suppressed romantic feelings between herself and Orsino: "Boy, thou hast told me a thousand times thou shouldst never love a woman like me." (5.1.260-261)

Although this might seem progressive, modern readers may interpret "Twelfth Night" as illustrating how deception can facilitate the revelation of hidden emotions, particularly regarding Olivia and Orsino. Certain passages hint that these characters may have unexpressed subconscious desires that Viola/Cesario's presence forces them to confront. For example, is Olivia attracted to Cesario because he appears to be a man, or does she secretly have feelings for women? It is more likely that Shakespeare's character Olivia parodies those of his time who judge others solely on appearance.

This is evidenced by how easily Olivia shifts her affections from Cesario to Sebastian, and starts viewing Cesario/Viola as family rather than a romantic interest: "A sister, you are she." (5.1.315)

German colonial rule was noted by various observers for its brutality, especially regarding the genocide of the Ovaherero and Nama in German South West Africa. Of course, such a broad entity as an entire colonial empire cannot be fully described with such a simple characterization. The German colonial empire was as diverse in its policies and ruling styles as it was in its geography. Educational provisions across the colonies were similarly varied. When the British took over German East Africa (Tanganyika) in 1919, they found a large population of educated and literate Africans. German educational efforts in Cameroon and other colonies were also praised by contemporary authors. The situation in South West Africa (present-day Namibia) presented a stark contrast. Unlike in East Africa, where the government established state schools and played a significant role in the education of the natives, in South West Africa the task of native education was almost entirely left to missionary societies that received limited government support. However, the government did invest significant resources in the education of Europeans in the colony, establishing a system of state schools and more heavily supporting and regulating missionary schools. These educational policies had long-lasting effects on South West Africa, even after German rule. While other German colonies boasted significant numbers of literate and educated Africans, in South West Africa "the overwhelming majority of the population remained untouched, uneducated, and illiterate." Various social, political, and economic factors led to the divergent experience of South West Africa. This paper seeks to expand the discussion by identifying these factors and paying particular attention to new research on the attitudes of settlers and colonial authorities towards native Africans. There is a wealth of literature specifically dealing with education in the German colonial empire. Most of these sources are in German and were written in the early twentieth century, during or shortly after the period of German colonial rule. The aim of early works was primarily to describe the features of educational systems in these colonies. Later writings in English expanded the discourse through comparative studies of education in the various German colonies and more detailed analyses of specific aspects of education. These studies illustrated significant differences in the educational systems of different colonies. The most prominent work to explicitly address the topic of this paper is Cohen’s study of education in South West Africa and East Africa. Cohen compares the educational systems of the two colonies and discusses the factors that account for the differences between them. According to Cohen, the large settler population of South West Africa explains many of the distinguishing aspects of the colony’s educational system. Compared to Germany’s other colonial possessions, South West Africa had a moderately temperate climate, although much of the territory is covered by arid desert. The European population of South West Africa reflected the relatively hospitable conditions. By 1913, nearly 15,000 whites lived in South West Africa, while only 5,336 lived in the colony with the next largest settler population, East Africa.

The United States of America and Mexico are examples of two countries that once experienced a long-standing rivalry lasting 57 years, from 1836 to 1893, as noted by Diehl and Goerts (2000, p. 145). The height of this rivalry was the Mexican-American War from 1846 to 1848, during which the United States invaded and defeated Mexico, claiming Texas and the American Southwest as new territories. Numerous other conflicts between the two nations occurred, finally subsiding just before the First World War. This rivalry was fueled by clashes over key issues such as religion, culture, tradition, and significant material interests (Schmitt 1974, pp. 30-31).

This scenario is similar to many other nations with enduring rivalries with their neighbors. Countries sharing borders tend to have conflicting interests, leading to rival positions. The United States and Mexico resemble many other long-standing rivalries between bordering nations. David M. Pletcher (1977) points out that "only in Mexico and Cuba can one find long-lasting overarching American diplomatic problems" (p. 41). Indeed, both of these countries are geographically close to the United States and have been its rivals, while other Latin American nations have enjoyed good relations with the United States.

Religious issues created a division between the two countries, a problem that has affected many nations throughout history. Sally Frahm (2001) notes that "if in the twentieth century Americans opposed fascism and communism, in the eighteenth and nineteenth centuries they opposed Catholicism and monarchy" (p.86). Similar to the Cold War rivalry between the United States and the Soviet Union, which was partially an ideological struggle and partially a competition over vital interests, the ideological conflict here was not about political structure but rather about religious preferences of the United States and Mexico. This distrust originated from the historical distrust between the English and the Spanish. Inheriting these feelings of distrust from their former colonial rulers was a significant obstacle in establishing amicable foreign relations between the United States and Mexico.

Diehl and Goerts (2000) cite 17 disputes between Mexico and the United States during the 57-year rivalry period. Most disputes during this period, as described by Diehl and Goerts, were territorial issues related to border raids from Mexican territory into the United States and other frontier problems. Border raids by bandits and outlaws on American border towns were a major issue until both countries exerted military force on their borders (Schmitt 1974, p. 97).

Schmitt (1974) explains that the rivalry between the two nations began to subside as "Mexico became clearly dependent on the United States in a substantial way" (p. 109), finally ending when American ambitions "shifted from territorial expansion to economic intervention in Mexico" (p.110) in the latter part of the 19th century.

Fifteen years ago, I was suddenly and unexpectedly disabled by an illness I never knew existed.

At that time, I was a nurse. I chose the profession due to a deeply rooted need for the security I lacked as a child. "You'll always be able to find work; people will always get sick," was the mantra I heard repeatedly as I reached adolescence and beyond. So, even though my dream was to be a scientist or a journalist, preferably a bit of both, I chose nursing.

Yet, there I was: 46 years old and single, no money in the bank, and unable to work. To this day, I remain disabled, and after 15 years of living on Social Security Disability, I have literally nothing left that I can call "mine." I get by, but every day is a struggle and an assault on my security, safety, and self-esteem. Nothing in my life is certain anymore, but there is one thing I know to be true: I could not have managed all these years without the help of my family and a few good friends, no matter how strong I was. Believe me, when true disaster strikes, you don't feel strong at all.

My point is that there will always be emergencies in life, both big and small. There are no guarantees, and no matter how well you prepare, some things are just too big to handle on your own.

I wholeheartedly agree that in the U.S., we need to stop putting all our hopes in big government's "basket"; Lord knows it's moldy and falling apart anyway. Yet, I would much rather see Americans learning to trust each other again—learning to help one another and to ask for help—rather than each of us individually rushing to the backyard to build fallout shelters.

Conservatives in the U.S. talk about the "rugged individualism" that built this country; but in truth, what kept our forefathers going in hard times wasn't rugged individualism, it was compassion, mutual respect, and the sharing of resources. The pioneers who crossed the Rockies in wagon trains didn't make it to the coast by going it alone.

So, by all means, be prepared. I am. I have a disaster kit; first aid supplies, water purification tablets, and plastic sheeting and duct tape for the windows in the event of a biological attack. I have several flashlights, all sorts of batteries, lots and lots of candles, waterproof matches, and canned goods too. If you have the land and resources for a small farm and the ability to can or preserve your own food—do it. It's a great idea, as is a wood stove, as long as you don't live in an apartment.

But while you're at it, get to know your neighbors.

Sometime in the fifth or sixth century BCE, a prince was born who would later be known as Buddha. Throughout his life, he renounced the world and attained enlightenment, and his teachings led to the creation of Buddhism, with Theravada Buddhism being the most orthodox branch. The religion is about two and a half thousand years old; it looks different today than it did during Buddha's lifetime. This is evident everywhere, such as in the Theravada nation of Sri Lanka, where the annual water-cutting ceremony takes place. Both monks and laypeople participate in this ceremony, which holds some religious significance, even though Buddha never taught about such a festivity. These differences range from superficial traditions to the core soteriological aspects of the religion. Over time, the Theravada Buddhist community, both from the monastic and lay perspectives, has had to modify its doctrinal principles. This can be attributed to both external and internal forces, whether hostile or benign.

There are several qualifying terms that will be frequently used in this discussion. There is the concept of internal versus external forces. Here, an internal force is defined as one originating from members of the Buddhasasana, regardless of monastic status. An external force is any force from non-Buddhists. A hostile force is one that harms or intends to harm the Buddhist community—a force stemming from a negative perception of Buddhism. A benign force is one that neither wishes to harm nor help the Buddhist community, though it might inadvertently do one or the other. These terms will recur throughout this discussion.

First, it is important to examine the basics of the religion—the doctrines at the core of Theravada Buddhism. Buddhists seek refuge in the triple gem of the Buddha, the Dhamma, and the Sangha. The Dhamma essentially consists of the Tripitaka—the three baskets—of Buddhist texts. The Sutta Pitaka contains all the Suttas, the Vinaya Pitaka contains the disciplinary rules, and the Abhidhamma Pitaka contains the metaphysical components of Buddhism. The metaphysical notions include concepts like Anatta—no soul, Dukkha—innate suffering in life, and Anicca—impermanence of everything. Only by recognizing these concepts can one end Sansara, the cycle of death and rebirth, which occurs continuously. Along with Sansara, lobha—desire, dosa—hatred, and moha—delusion will end when one becomes enlightened. The Vinaya Pitaka sets forth rules for life. For laypeople, there are five precepts (I shall not kill, I shall not lie, I shall not steal, I shall not behave sexually improperly, and I shall not take intoxicating substances). For monks, there are many more disciplinary rules to follow. The most fundamental doctrinal notion in Buddhism is the concept of the four noble truths. First, Dukkha; the truth that life is suffering. Second, that attachment causes suffering. Third, that suffering can be overcome.
