When borrowers defaulted on these loans, banks were short on capital reserves and passed this chaos onto the repackaged mortgages they had sold, impacting the rest of the economy.

The financial crisis had its roots in the Clinton era of 1999, as the President aimed for a second term in office. He sought to extend his presidency by boosting his popularity. To achieve this, the Clinton administration relaxed lending restrictions, which helped set the stage for the sub-prime crisis seven years later. Steven Holmes of the New York Times reported in 1999, "Fannie Mae, the nation's largest underwriter of home mortgages, has been under increasing pressure from the Clinton Administration to expand mortgage loans among low and moderate-income people and felt pressure from shareholders to maintain its phenomenal growth in profits." Holmes correctly predicted the consequences of these actions: "But the government-subsidized corporation may run into trouble in an economic downturn, prompting a government rescue similar to that of the savings and loan industry in the 1980s." As detailed in the introduction and as Holmes foresaw, ill-advised lending would certainly lead to the meltdown of the economy.

Numerous factors combined to throw the economy into a tailspin, one of which was the new and complex structure of mortgages. Adjustable-rate mortgages, mortgage-backed securities, and collateralized debt obligations (CDOs) were extensively used in the years leading to the crisis and only served to entangle more sectors of the economy with the housing market. This led U.S. households, and financial markets in general, to over-leverage themselves in the housing market, making them extremely vulnerable to even small price changes.

Indeed, the housing bubble burst, and the financial institutions that had bought these mortgage-backed securities were adversely affected. The top five U.S. investment banks collectively reported $4.1 trillion in mortgage debts in 2007, accounting for about 30% of the USA's GDP. Ultimately, Bear Stearns and Merrill Lynch were sold at exceptionally low prices, Lehman Brothers was dismantled, and Goldman Sachs and Morgan Stanley were forced to become commercial banks subject to intense regulation. Fannie and Freddie held $5 trillion in mortgage debt and were placed under government control in September 2008.

Ah, exposition. That section of your story where you unleash your writerly talents and dazzle everyone with your captivating, even enchanting prose. Or perhaps it's the part where your readers nod off and/or hit the "Back" button muttering your name in frustration. Dr. Merlin is known for shouting at her monitor when she's caught in the middle of an overload of information, and not in an enjoyable way.

Exposition is not your ally.

My gentle readers are already familiar with the basic writing tip, "Show, don't tell," yet Dr. Merlin still finds herself in lengthy passages where nothing happens or, worse, too much occurs. Exposition is the little devil on your shoulder telling you to get the history out of the way to reach the exciting parts (not to be confused with the devil on the other shoulder urging the author to detail every childhood moment of each character).

Exposition involves telling the audience what happened, typically in straightforward prose. In film, this happens when a character bombards another with a flood of information, much like "The Rime of the Ancient Mariner." In fiction, it's the author doing the telling.

An example to illustrate. As you read a story, you're informed that the heroine met her beloved at a specific time and place, that they married in grand style, and that her husband was murdered before her eyes. You wouldn't expect this entire sequence to span two pages, during which both characters only utter two lines of dialogue each. You would expect the author to delve into the husband's character, demonstrating through his words and actions how deeply he loves his wife, and you would equally expect the heroine to reveal through various means how much his presence transformed and enriched her life (especially if the story later explicitly states this). A thorough introduction to the husband's character would allow you to become emotionally invested in his fate and provide insights into the heroine's character: what she saw in him, the depth of their bond, clues about her thoughts, beliefs, and dreams as seen through his eyes, and so forth. You would grieve his death with her, thus deepening your connection to the heroine herself.

In essence, you would expect substance on the bare bones of the storyline: "They met, they married, he died."

As a writer, you need to flesh out those bones. (*glances at metaphor, sighs, proceeds*) Sometimes it's tempting to gloss over certain details. Perhaps you're introducing a new character and you know he was once in the Air Force, is now the night manager of a gas station, has been married twice, has no children, enjoys fishing on weekends, secretly dreams of owning the gas station one day, and had Eggs Benedict for breakfast.

I watched two news broadcasts from Columbus, Ohio. The first one, which aired "live," was NBC 4 this morning (August 13, 2011). The main story was about a man in Ashley, Ohio who had stabbed his wife. Her name wasn't mentioned, but his name was Shad Hostettler. They showed his mug shot, and he looked like pure evil. They spent only about two minutes on this story as it was still developing. The only details given were that he had stabbed her multiple times and had been arrested. I think they devoted an appropriate amount of time on this story.

The second story was about an early morning shooting of Travis Buyers, aged 18. He was shot in the Sharon Woods area and was critically injured; no arrests had been made at that time, nor were there any suspects. The SWAT team was investigating the crime. This story seemed short, and I believe this might have been because he was a "black" man or it was a black neighborhood. I've noticed (and have for years) that minorities are often overlooked when they are victims of crime. If, for example, a "white" child or adult is kidnapped, missing, or a crime victim, the media goes into a frenzy; but if it's a minority individual, it's lucky if it's even mentioned.

The next story was about a gunshot hole found in a Med-Flight helicopter. Details were provided about where they thought the incident occurred. It was determined that a .22 caliber bullet from a rifle had hit the helicopter. Crime-Stoppers are offering a five-thousand dollar reward for tips leading to the shooter's arrest.

The next story was about the rain and thunderstorms forecasted for Saturday afternoon. They said temperatures would remain in the mid to low eighties for the weekend. The segment was a bit short, but they wanted to use it as a "teaser" to keep the audience watching.

They also reported a robbery at a Clime Road UDF in Columbus. They said it was a dark-skinned black man who robbed the store, wearing a hoodie sweatshirt. He was described as about six feet tall and weighing around one hundred and fifty pounds. I thought they spent an unusual amount of time emphasizing his race and how dark-skinned he was.

Another story was about Rene Rodriguez, a convicted Texas drug kingpin. He had been convicted of conspiring to distribute large amounts of marijuana from Texas to Ohio. One curious thing I noted was that instead of saying he was sentenced to twenty-five years in prison, they said "300" months. I'm not sure what the angle was there, whether they thought it sounded harsher or what. They also mentioned he was a Hispanic man, which I don't think was really relevant to the story.

An ETF, or exchange-traded fund, is a financial instrument designed to track an index, a commodity, or a basket of assets like an index fund but is more flexible and trades like a stock on an exchange. An ETF offers the diversification of an index fund and the benefits of owning individual stocks, such as the ability to short sell, buy on margin, and purchase as little as one share in any transaction. Although these benefits are highly attractive, ETFs have much lower expense ratios than the average mutual fund. Unfortunately, there are some drawbacks, such as the need to pay a commission on any trade involving ETFs, just as you would with a stock order. Another advantage of ETFs is the wide range of available funds. Although these benefits are clearly outlined, it is always a good exercise for the savvy financial investor to assess whether the stated benefits, like diversification, actually exist and to what extent they do. For the purposes of this endeavor, we will be examining the ETF IHF and comparing it to the top 10 holdings that make up the ETF to determine if the benefits of owning a single ETF are close to the benefits of owning a diversified portfolio of the ten stocks and whether there might be better configurations of the same stocks that could offer a more optimal Sharpe ratio or return.

To evaluate the ETF, it would be quite cumbersome to include every holding, so we have decided to include only the top ten holdings, which account for 63.58% of all the assets in the ETF. Below are the top 10 holdings and the percentage of total assets.

To estimate how well these ten stocks represent the ETF IHF as a whole, we can use the current percentage of assets, normalized to 100%, to calculate each stock's contribution to a portfolio's Beta and Return if the portfolio consisted entirely of these 10 stocks in the proportion established by the ETF. The calculations of Beta and return are included in the chart below.

From the above chart, it is evident that the return of a portfolio containing only the top 10 holdings is 6.11% higher than the ETF, a 16% increase in returns. It is also clear that the Beta of the top ten holdings is 0.12 lower than that of the entire ETF. From the results obtained so far, it seems that a portfolio of just the top 10 holdings could provide a higher return with a lower beta. However, there is a possibility that the means of these two portfolios may not be statistically different from each other.

To evaluate whether these portfolios are statistically different, the standard deviation of each of the top 10 stocks is determined and normalized to 100% to compare their accumulated standard deviation to that of the ETF IHF.

Referring back to Figure 17, there was a steep decline in commuter log submissions during the third month of the project. This was somewhat discouraging, and it's hard to pinpoint why it might have happened. With the onset of winter at a New England campus, there's clearly a decrease in people commuting by bicycle or on foot, which could explain part of the drop. December also marks the end of the fall semester when everyone is very busy completing schoolwork and processing grades. Filling out the commuter log might have simply slipped off the radar for many. Additionally, December brings the start of the busy holiday season and the resulting month-long break for students and faculty, during which many don't need to come to campus at all. Classes resume for the spring semester in late January, which might also provide a clue to the low number of logs in that month. But all of this doesn't really explain the low number of submissions in February. One might also speculate that any project of this kind experiences an initial surge of energy and excitement that naturally wanes. To counteract this trend, we created the Carpool Challenge Week, a special blitz campaign in March to try to reinvigorate the initiative, which resulted in an increase in log submissions for that month. Thus, one of the challenges we faced was how to maintain project momentum in light of both a natural decrease in engagement and the specific issue of holiday and semester breaks in higher education. Another challenge for this project (or any alternative commuting project) is the simple fact that people enjoy the freedom, independence, and flexibility of driving their cars. This is deeply ingrained in our culture. Therefore, it's essential to offer incentives for engaging in alternative commuting modes. We gave out many prizes in the form of gift certificates to local restaurants, coffee shops, massage therapists, the local independent bookstore, and even some larger national chain stores. It would have been interesting to see how some even larger prizes might have affected participation – such as giving away a nice bicycle, hybrid car, or electric car. This could have also helped to counter the dip in engagement the project experienced. The nature of the prizes didn't really change during the course of the project. However, if the prizes had increased in value over the course of the project, that might have helped. The gift cards seemed to be more than sufficient at the start of the project, but if we had announced in December the addition of a couple of bicycles, and then in January the addition of a hybrid or electric car, one can only think that participation and engagement would have increased instead of decreased.

While exploring the Library of Congress's collection of early Edison films, I decided to watch all the trick films, of which there were fifteen from 1895 to 1901. These films typically use creative editing techniques to create illusions. My film analysis mainly focused on describing the poetic elements of most trick films and examining the evolutionary outlier features present in some of the later films. Generally, trick films at the turn of the century are bound to a set, composed within a frontal proscenium, feature no camera movement, use long and medium shots, and adhere to a strict one shot = one film methodology. However, some films from the early twentieth century dared to break these guidelines by introducing aspects such as multiple shots.

One of the most noticeable features shared by the trick films is filming in an interior set within the frame of a frontal proscenium. The camera does not move from its proscenium position to follow figures or objects. This composition was very common in early films and has its roots in theater and, for trick films, vaudeville and magic acts. A limitation inherent in the use of the stage is that figures in trick films generally only move side-to-side and do not walk towards or away from the camera. Take, for example, the action in the film Uncle Josh in a Spooky Hotel (1900). The actors enter from the right side and move back and forth along the horizontal axis. Even as they leave the frame, the camera does not follow them.

The frontal proscenium style of composition also means that shots tend to be long shots and, more rarely, medium shots. Close-up shots are never used in any of the trick films from the Edison catalog. This borrows from the tradition of theater and vaudeville, where the audience would see the entire performance at any given time, framed by the stage's borders. As in most early films, the actors do not move from the middle ground towards the camera, so close-ups never occur.

Generally, most early trick films follow the pattern that one conceptual shot equals a film. This limits the length of most trick films to about a minute or less, depending on the frames per second used. It also limits the dramatic or narrative use of the trick films; most focus on short vaudeville-style tricks, like magic, disappearing, and switching acts with little story. Note, however, that in a trick film, one conceptual shot in the viewer's eyes does not actually equal one physical shot. A single "shot" may actually be several joined together to create the illusion of appearing or disappearing. Look carefully at The Execution of Mary, Queen of Scots (1895), one of the earlier trick films. A more thorough inspection reveals the moment where the physical shot with Mary's severed "head" begins, even though the whole film is conceptually one shot to the viewer.

The traditional "Gothic Novel" is essentially an "oxymoron for 'Old-New,'" as Ian Watt explains in "The Rise of the Gothic Novel." The Gothic style has been criticized, praised, accused of lacking depth, and celebrated for its 'terrible sublime' aspect (Burke). Horace Walpole's "The Castle of Otranto," the original "Gothic Novel," combined elements of both ancient and modern romances to create the proto-Gothic genre and a new form of literary expression. Walpole blends "old" theatrical elements with 'new' mimicry of nature in 'modern' novels to present what he calls "A Gothic Story" (Walpole 4). The Gothic genre draws heavily on medieval gothic theater, architecture, and traditions. At the time "The Castle of Otranto" was published, "gothic" was used to describe various peoples, styles, and periods. It was seen as archaic or unsophisticated compared to "modern" societal and literary "advancements." The combination of theatrical "Gothic" elements with the novel's new format (providing a personal view of the characters' psychology) allows Gothic literature to endure, becoming both obsolete and new to readers distanced in time from its original writing.

One of the most prominent Gothic ideas in Gothic novels is the concept of chivalry. The medieval notion of chivalry, training a proper knight, is both preserved and transformed in the original Gothic novel, "The Castle of Otranto." Chivalry is crucial for Gothic writers because of what it represented—the classic knight, brave, honorable, competent—and the perceived lack of that ideal that writers (particularly Walpole) saw in society. Through the use of chivalric concepts and manners, the "gothic past" is idealized and romanticized (hinting at the evolution from Gothic to Romantic) and used to attempt to improve the present. When Walpole wrote "The Castle of Otranto," he was in a politically troubled time and despaired over the potential future. Engaged in politics and (arguably) facing unfair accusations, he may have started to believe, even if not explicitly, that the supposed morality and inherent "goodness" of people from the Gothic era had somehow been lost in the 'present' society. This concept is evident in his writing through characters like Frederic. Before meeting Frederic, the reader can tell he embodies many chivalric traits, as he is described as:

His description includes many traditionally chivalric images; Frederic is foremost a prince, has suffered, been affected by tragedy, and is believed to have been killed by infidels. The figure of the "gallant and courteous Knight" is, naturally, exaggerated, introducing the soon-to-be Gothic trope of excess (66).

Supply chain management involves the flow of processes that move goods from the customer order through the raw materials phase to delivery, production, and distribution to the customer. The term was coined by consultant Keith Oliver in 1982. He described the entire process of planning, implementing, and controlling what happens in the supply chain to meet customer needs quickly and efficiently. There are six key elements in a supply chain: production, supply, inventory, location, transportation, and information. Business managers use these key elements to provide the best customer service.

Production is the first step in the supply chain process and forms the foundation for the entire chain. It outlines when, why, where, and how everything will be produced. Managers need to understand customer desires, which can be determined by observing the market. The market serves as the largest indicator of customer demands. Once managers have analyzed the market and understood customer demand, they are prepared to decide which products to produce and in what quantities. After deciding on what and how much to produce, they determine where production should occur and which plant is best suited for volume and quality, keeping customer demand and satisfaction in mind. Once the production location is determined, managers focus on scheduling workloads and maintaining equipment. Production is a crucial step in the supply chain process, with every detail being vital. Poor planning can cost the company time and money in the long run. For instance, during my time at Wal-Mart and Target, both companies had a design, manual, and process for every business aspect, from how employee uniforms should look to receiving shipments from trucks. Outlined processes help a company operate smoothly without confusion over direction and expectations.

The second key element in supply chain management is supply. Supply involves strategic decisions that determine the core capabilities of a facility, and outsourcing partnerships should stem from these decisions. A company may have various production divisions for a single product, each with different equipment, workers, and specialties. The manager must decide which division best suits the different processes involved. Management might also choose to outsource work to other companies. The main reason for outsourcing is to create speed, which is the ability to provide quality and flexibility while reducing costs or maintaining low cost levels.

Victorian novels are known for their meticulous attention to detail and their focus on the aristocracy of the time. Two novels that are considered Victorian but deviate from this tradition are Oliver Twist and Wuthering Heights. Both novels incorporate an element of mystery and a penchant for the bizarre, which is atypical for novels of that era, strengthening the characters within each work and providing insight into their motives and emotions.

"And now, hosts of bewildering and confusing ideas flooded his mind. He seemed to still be walking between Sikes and Crackit, who were angrily disputing: for the very words they uttered rang in his ears; and when he focused on himself, he found that he was speaking to them... Suddenly he recoiled at the sound of gunfire; loud cries and shouts rose into the air; lights flashed before his eyes, and everything was noise and turmoil, as some unseen hand hurriedly bore him away. Through all these rapid visions ran an undefined, uneasy consciousness of pain, which wearied and tormented him incessantly." (Dickens, 220)

The two novels often use this mystery through dream sequences or dreamlike states, although the content and function vary in each specific case. In Oliver Twist, these strange occurrences often reveal insights into Oliver’s inner layers, what pains him, and his awareness of the true nature of the happenings around him. When the shooting of Oliver is revisited in chapter 28, Oliver relives the shooting vividly, as if in a dream, while he struggles to find help. The passage highlights the lack of control Oliver had over the unfolding events, as well as the dire state of his health, which was strongly present via Oliver’s hallucinations of Sikes and Crackit. The shooting itself overwhelms him, numbing all his senses as he does not notice the "unseen hand" that bears him away; he experiences his despair again, detached from the shock of pain, as the pain is now constant and linked with fear rather than surprise. With Oliver being overwhelmed, the question arises as to whose will caused his misfortune, as it certainly was not his own. This shooting reinforces the notion that Oliver has little control over anything, as he cannot even attempt to influence the outcome of an event, even when his life is in danger. A growing sense of defeat in Oliver is also implied by this selection, as if old Fagin had begun to break him, forcing him to accept this despair, affecting his ability to react. For otherwise, it can be assumed that Oliver would have made some effort, at least for the sake of his own life.

"The day passed off – day! There was no day; it was gone as soon as it came – and night came on again; night so long, and yet so short; long in its dreadful silence and short in its fleeting hours."

A few years ago, I worked in an after-school program tutoring elementary school students. I did my best to help them in any subject they were struggling with, but my strengths were in English and reading. One of the instructors asked me to help a little boy named Adrian (I believe he was in third or fourth grade) who was having significant trouble reading. It dawned on me that something was wrong; he had the most peculiar issues. Some letters he could pronounce perfectly, others not at all, it was the strangest thing. You know, he was of Latino descent, that was clear to me, but the boy spoke perfect English. We struggled on until the day I met his mother. I was helping to supervise a few kids (for lack of a better term) while the rest of the after-school group was on a field trip when his mother came in. His mother didn't speak a word of English, only Spanish. With my very poor Spanish (I was just learning it), we managed to communicate. But then it hit me like a ton of bricks: Adrian could read just fine, he just didn't know the English alphabet very well. I don't know if that realization helped him much, but I do hope he is doing better now.

I tell this story to address the issue of language barriers in schools, especially here in California. I also tell it to prove that it isn't always as obvious as we might think. Even for a child who speaks perfect English, reading can still be a major obstacle. I think everyone can agree that this problem exists, so what do we do? In Adrian's case, the solution was fairly simple: tutoring in English reading, especially the alphabet and pronunciations. But for the many children who barely speak English, the solution is much more complex. There is no single answer. The dual language system, mainstream immersion, private tutors, ESL classes, none of these alone will solve this problem. The key lies in combining all of the above!

First of all, the dual language system is a great idea. Not just for children whose first language is Spanish, but for all children. "Children in two-way bilingual education programs have been found to outperform their peers academically." A lot of fear surrounds this idea, that it's a waste of resources and that the majority of children in schools will not benefit. But that's false. If we were to apply these kinds of programs in the classroom as the rule rather than the exception, all children would benefit from it. How do we approach this? Do we require all teachers to be bilingual? No. That would be unreasonable and somewhat unrealistic. However, I do think there's no reason we can't have special aides, tutors, whatever you want to call them, who are bilingual.

From the time we are children, most of us hear there's something out there larger than ourselves, beyond our comprehension. Some attend Sunday school to learn about it, others go to temples or seek answers within. Many of us accept the religions passed down by our parents, but some reject them entirely, denying anything beyond our own limited universe. We might adopt one belief system and later shift to another. Whatever path we take, we journey to define part of ourselves through our unique spiritual perspectives. We seek a light in the darkness to lead us from shadows into sunlight.

"A cardinal," my father said when I asked about his favorite bird. We sat on the front porch, listening to rain pound on the tin roof as we smoked together. The gutters carried the rain down, drowning plants along the porch's edge. He looked into the rain with a gaze that was part searching, part remembering. Over the months, he'd grown thinner, his clothes hanging loosely. His hair was sparser than I remembered. He continued to stare into the rain, avoiding eye contact. I felt alone, scared, unable to tell my father how much I'd miss him, because speaking of it would make it too real for us both. I hugged him, sat back down, moved my chair closer, and joined him watching the rain fall in the June twilight.

My father died that December, five days after my twenty-second birthday. Chemotherapy and radiation hadn't eased his suffering, but prolonged his life slightly beyond what doctors predicted; I couldn't see the value in his extended suffering. What kind of God would allow this, I wondered. Alone at night, I offered no prayers. If God existed, I felt, He'd stopped listening to me long ago.

I didn't want to watch him transition from this life to another, so I didn't. I couldn't watch the life that created me as it ended. I wanted to remember him by how he lived, not how he died. I knew my father better than they did, better than his family, and knew he wouldn't want his only child to witness his death. I curled up in bed for three days, waiting for the news.

No one even called.

John Taylor of Caroline was an early and passionate advocate of Republicanism. Though primarily a farmer, his profession, along with his brief political career, made him known for his dedication and open expression on issues of personal freedom and government. His commitment to an agrarian system formed the basis for nearly all of his views on government. It was his attempt to preserve and promote what he considered the most superior of all careers that shaped his arguments on sovereignty, constitutionality, and even the judicial system.

John Taylor believed that the United States had a great opportunity to create an ideal system because there was no native tradition to hinder the creators of government, allowing for the establishment of a system of self-government. He strongly believed in the natural rights of man and that they are all interdependent—meaning that if one is denied, they all will fail, diminishing the value of those that remain. Therefore, these rights should be beyond the reach of government. He claimed that what some called the "state of nature" meant that those with physical strength and malevolent intelligence were the ones who profited, but in a civilization, this must not be the way.

To create this ideal society, Taylor believed that a government must be formed that accounts for the inherent good and evil within man. Taylor was very steadfast in his views on dualistic morality. He claimed that "since government is exercised by man, all its virtues and vices must be human." He defined good principles as those that protect private property, improve agriculture, and discourage capitalism, and believed that a government founded on good principles would function equitably regardless of its administration, which would inevitably be led by greed and self-interest. He believed self-interest was man's motivation in all things, but that the trait was only considered evil when it led beyond the creation of a society based on the public good to sub-societies that lived at the expense of others. A good government was necessary to contain man's natural evil, and even then, it must be closely monitored to prevent the addition of bad principles.

Taylor, like many other staunch Republicans of his time, called for a strict interpretation of the Constitution. He wanted an extremely limited Federal government, with no more rights or powers granted to it than those explicitly stated in the Constitution. He knew that an extensive Federal government was expensive and therefore likely to be despotic. However, he believed that a simple, literal interpretation was dangerous, and that without reference to the intent of the writers, such a method could easily become corrupt. Moreover, he considered the Declaration of Independence the true charter of the United States because it more explicitly describes the country as a group of sovereign states rather than one nation.

Downwards I stared, my mind blankly absorbing the view in front of me. Without emotion, silently, with a practiced awareness that observed but refused to connect the object of study to any abstract understanding, my mind analyzed the image before my eyes. Thoughts drifted into my mind and out again almost as quickly as they arrived. So smoothly and cleanly did my consciousness operate that it seemed I had no real thoughts of my own, just an active and fluid experience of what I was observing. 

Once, following the advice of an artist I worked with, I bought an art instruction book titled The New Drawing on the Right Side of the Brain. I had wanted to learn to draw since I was six years old, and this book teaches everything from understanding what a pencil is to the brain processes used to interpret lines. One technique the book teaches is to place a square frame around any picture the artist wishes to study. This transforms an overwhelmingly detailed picture, like a bowl of fruit on a table in a kitchen connected to a dining room, into an easily understandable picture, that bowl of fruit on a simple plane.

At that moment, staring down at the bowl in front of me, I couldn't mentally project that artist’s frame. I was so overwhelmed, so awed, that I could only stand and gaze in wonder. Picasso went through his blue period, Monet loved greenery, and Italian Renaissance masters displayed a rainbow of colors. If I had any pretensions of considering my perspective worthy of the title Artistic, then before me were the beginnings of my picture, the start of my story, Work in Brown.

Fingertips touched my chosen tool of artistry, muscles tightened and relaxed as my hand moved through space, my mind’s will given shape and form in what might have been the most creative moment of my life. Water swirled, serene and smooth, crystal clear and clean. Flakes of matter broke away and were carried away to nothingness. Muscles tightened, jerking and spasming a bit more quickly and anxiously the second time, as my hand hit the handle of the toilet again. The offending brown package refused to move, stuck like a slug at the bottom of the toilet.

Mop loosely held in hand, feet set a foot apart, green tie uncomfortably knotted around my throat, I frowned slightly as I stared at the rude bundle of processed animal and plant matter left as a message for the unfortunate souls who cleaned the bathrooms at Rite Aid. A few more flushes, a few more tranquil introspective moments to myself, then my hand moved towards the wall to my right, gripped the end sheet of the toilet paper, and began wrapping itself until it resembled an oven mitt. Standing up straight, then bending at the waist, my hand dipped slowly into the bowl, like a mother reaching into an oven for the Thanksgiving turkey...

Teenagers are losing their lives behind the wheel. Several factors converge to create this grim statistic for America's youngest drivers. The National Institutes of Health point out that one part of the problem is that the teenage brain is literally not equipped for the dangers of driving. Simple lack of experience is also a major issue. This inexperience not only leads to more fatal accidents, but also to higher rates of vehicle rollovers, speeding, and going off the road.

Teens also perform much worse when traveling with their peers, which everyone with any common sense knows they do regularly. The Southern California Injury Prevention Research Center conducted a study showing a correlation between the age of passengers and the number of traffic accidents.

California and other states have tried to increase teen driver safety by implementing temporary provisional licenses that limit the hours teens can drive and prohibit other minors as passengers.

However, in my opinion, provisional licenses are only temporary fixes. The core issue is that, as a group, the youngest drivers are simply not capable of adequately handling the risks and responsibilities, according to all statistical measures. Psychologist Marvin Zuckerman believes even 18 is too young for a regular driver's license. USA Today reports that Zuckerman's research suggests that those under 19-20 have a common desire to take risks for the thrill of it. Therefore, it makes sense to delay driving until the thrill-seeking tendency begins to diminish. If we continue issuing licenses to young teens, not only will deadly accidents persist, but the death toll is likely to become staggering in the coming years. By 2010, the children of Baby Boomers will be eligible to drive, and millions of new teen drivers will be ready to hit the road.

Legislation addressing this issue could be relatively straightforward. Schools could continue offering driver's education to start the learning process for future drivers, but no one under 18 could operate a vehicle. A provisional license could be issued before granting a full driver's license, and a specific number of practical driving hours would still be required. The exact number of hours could be based on what most states currently require (for example, in California, it's currently 6 hours of in-car training and 50 hours of practice with an adult). Since the deadly statistics for teen drivers come from all states, uniform national legislation on this issue would be a reasonable—and, I believe, effective—way to protect teens across the country.

The legislation I propose is by no means a novel idea.

This article examines three aspects of Central Auditory Processing Disorder (CAPD). First, a brief definition of the disorder is given. Then, the diagnosis is explained, highlighting common features or "red flags". Finally, the article outlines how a teacher in an inclusive classroom setting can support a student with CAPD.

Central Auditory Processing Disorder (CAPD), also known as Auditory Processing Disorder (APD), refers to how efficiently and effectively the central nervous system (CNS) uses auditory information. Narrowly defined, (C)AP involves the perceptual processing of auditory information in the CNS and the neurobiological activity underlying this processing, which results in electrophysiological auditory potentials (American Speech-Language-Hearing Association, 2005). This means it is a disorder where the central nervous system (i.e., the brain) is unable to properly process what is heard. People with CAPD can hear normally and are thus not considered "hearing impaired"; rather, the area of the brain responsible for translating what we hear, distinguishing words, or separating conversations from background noise does not function as it typically should.

The earliest reference to what became known as CAPD dates back to the mid-1950s, when it was referred to as "auditory imperception" as researchers studied children with communication disorders. The Italian research team of Bocca, Calearo, and Cassinari began developing tests for these children in 1954; in 1961, Kimura introduced "dichotic testing and formulated a model to explain the physiology of the central auditory nervous system underlying dichotic perception" (American Speech-Language-Hearing Association, 2005). A national conference in 1977 spurred research into children with CAPD.

CAPD manifests in various ways: the affected person may be unable to localize or hear sound in space; may have difficulty distinguishing between two or more "acoustic events" (sound occurrences); may not recognize sound patterns; may be unable to detect changes in speech (such as identifying sarcasm through voice changes); one sound may be blocked by another subsequent sound; may lack the ability to synthesize auditory clues (i.e., interpret them meaningfully in order to respond); and may be unable to determine the sequence in which auditory information is presented (Ferre).

To diagnose CAPD, the patient must undergo "systematic observation of listening behavior and/or performance on tests of auditory function," which can be conducted by "audiologists, speech-language pathologists, psychologists, and others using various measures that evaluate auditory-related skills" (American Speech-Language-Hearing Association, 2005). This may include questionnaires and surveys, observation of auditory behaviors, including how the patient responds to certain stimuli. Currently, there is no single tool or test that consistently achieves a high rate of diagnostic success, and there is no known cause for the disorder. Many tests present the patient with multiple, simultaneous auditory stimuli and then ask them to differentiate specific items, such as a series of words or numbers. More advanced tests include recording acoustic signals within the ear and measuring responses to these signals.

In pursuing an education in social work, I plan to follow a career with the Division of Family and Children Services to assist children who have been abused or neglected, and to support troubled families. Values I can bring to the field of social work include: service, respect, ethical principles, commitment to improving relationships with others, and professional development to remain competent in my field. These core values are not only important to social workers; they hold personal significance for me.

I have always wanted to help others, but I was uncertain about the career path I wanted to take. Throughout my high school and college years, I saw many people escape their problems in denial, and some used less than ideal coping mechanisms. Because of situations I have witnessed, I chose to pursue a Bachelor's degree in Psychology. Still unsure of a career path, I decided to take a break after graduating from Piedmont College in 2009. One summer day, I visited a friend who introduced me to a sixteen-year-old boy nervously sitting on her couch. She explained why he was visiting: to escape his abusive parents. The next day, I learned that he had called the police to his parents’ home. To see if I could help, I drove to his parents' house. Once there, I privately expressed my concerns to the police and told them I had just graduated with a degree in Psychology from Piedmont College. The police asked me to speak with the parents since the law couldn’t help the teenager. When I questioned the parents about the situation, they appeared nervous and made excuses to describe their son's "manipulative" behavior for involving outside sources to resolve "simple" disputes. After this particular experience, I seriously began to consider a career in social work to help children with "simple" disputes among family members.

Another important value for the field of social work is social justice. As a society, we claim the individual is important and we mourn those we have lost. The concept of the "individual" in society is more a follower of archaic traditions than true uniqueness. So, if society mourns lost individuals, why do we strive to be like "everyone else?" I am an individual and do not enjoy limiting myself to be similar to others. Throughout my high school and college years, I protested against social injustice whenever I could: coloring my hair unnatural colors, wearing clothing that fit my personality, piercing my ears beyond the traditional set, declaring my involvement with the GSBA (Gay Straight Bisexual Alliance), fighting against racism and discrimination whenever I saw it, etc. I believe in social justice and will continue to protest against social injustice.

The paper discusses biological and sociocultural models concerning the sleep disorder insomnia. The biological model emphasizes inherited genetic information and medical aspects of health. Sociocultural models examine environmental interactions and their relation to race, ethnicity, demographics, and socioeconomic status. This insomnia review examines these models and explains each research piece selected to relate to and elucidate the models. The explanations of the research and their findings are critiqued to highlight specific strengths and weaknesses.

A sleep disorder may be classified as a primary sleep disorder, a sleep disorder related to another mental disorder, or a sleep disorder related to other issues. Primary sleep disorders include Dyssomnias or Parasomnias, while sleep disorders related to another mental disorder are associated with Axis I or Axis II disorders. Other sleep disorder categories may be due to medical complications or substance intake. Dyssomnias include: Primary Insomnia, Primary Hypersomnia, Narcolepsy, Breathing-Related Sleep Disorder, Circadian Rhythm Sleep Disorder, and Dyssomnia Not Otherwise Specified (NOS). Primary Insomnia involves difficulty in having enough or consistent sleep, while Primary Hypersomnia involves difficulty staying awake, both lasting for at least one month. Narcolepsy involves cataplexy and/or automatic REM. While Dyssomnias focus on initiating and maintaining sleep, Parasomnias are associated with behavioral and/or physiological abnormalities. Parasomnias include Nightmare Disorder, Sleep Terror Disorder, Sleepwalking Disorder, and Parasomnias Not Otherwise Specified. Sleep disorders related to another mental disorder involve sleep difficulties due to Axis I (Clinical Disorders) or Axis II (Personality Disorders or Intellectual Disability). This review focuses on insomnia and somewhat on primary sleep disorders in connection with biological and sociocultural models.

The biological model of sleep disorders focuses on genes, heritable factors, and physiologically acquired aspects of sleep disorders. Neurons in the hypothalamus containing orexin are responsible for regulating sleep and wakefulness. This study experimented with mice and found phenotypic GABAB receptors on orexin neurons specifically responsible for sleep/wake states. Activation of the GABAA receptor induces responses that promote sleep. If its firing is inhibited, it can reduce anxiety and promote sleep. The GABAB agonist (baclofen) increased sleep time (Matsuki et al., 2009). Such results suggest that mouse animal models can be generalized to human studies. This indicates a genetic and environmental basis for the physical GABAB receptor in humans. A problem or absence of this receptor could impair the ability to have adequate sleep without medication. The sociocultural implication of this study is that if the phenotype is inherited, it could regulate sleep, and an alteration of the receptor would naturally disturb an individual's sleep. This would negatively impact aspects of life such as school, career, and everyday events requiring monotonous tasks and focus.

I have been a student at University Park for around two and a half years now, or four and a half semesters. For many, myself included, getting around campus can be challenging. My first year, I was placed in an East Halls dorm room; basically the farthest eastern edge of campus, not counting the stadium and Bryce Jordan Center. Walking from my home in Stuart Hall to classes in places as distant as the Willard building, near the center of campus, could take up to 25 minutes, especially if the weather was bad, which it often is in State College. Talking to an alumnus not much older than me, I found out that not long ago, the East Halls dorms were separated from the rest of the school by large tracts of unused land. Today, that empty space is filled with sports fields, large new buildings including the new Creamery and health services building, and is surrounded by apartments. As our campus continues to grow, getting from one place to another becomes increasingly difficult. What is the best solution to the mobility issue? On a college campus, it's the bicycle. But just having bikes won't solve the problems. Students need to use them, and the campus needs to be designed to meet the needs of cyclists. I talked to a friend who recently started biking again after a several-year break. He mentioned that he wondered why he ever stopped. “Bikes are great,” he said, “for some years it wasn’t cool to ride a bike, but it’s the only way to get around.” Besides being good for your health, cycling is the most efficient way to travel. A bowl of oatmeal and a bit of physical effort can take you 30 miles or more. Like many undergraduates, I now live off-campus; just as far from the center of campus as some dorms. The smartest decision I made this year was to buy a bike. Every day, I have class in the Thomas building, a walk of twenty-five minutes from my home. Riding a bike can reduce that time to 5 minutes if I pedal fast enough. The only issue is that Pollock Road is the most direct route to the Thomas building from my house, and it's not always an easy road to travel, with or without a bike. Walking has its merits too, but I'm personally too busy to walk. Without my bike, walking would be my only reliable way to get to class. Walking to Thomas every day would take an additional 30-40 minutes out of my day. That’s over two and a half hours each week. Add to that all the other time I would need to spend walking to and from other classes, appointments, etc. That's more time than I can afford.

Aldous Huxley criticizes the looming threat of both technology and the capitalist structure, which is reinforced by creating a dystopia in the novel Brave New World. The people value the community over the individual and are conditioned from the start to seek immediate happiness above all else. The citizens are revealed to be pawns in a larger game, confined to a single ideology as dictated by the World Controller. When examining the work through the lens of Marxist theism, one notices the author's underlying suspicions regarding the development of these systems. Frequent Marxist terminology, such as homogeneity and reification, reinforces the idea that Huxley’s novel is a commentary on the flaws in the emerging economy of his time.

Capitalism is satirized through the use of the Marxist thesis of false consciousness. Essentially, the common citizens are prevented from understanding true relations to other classes in economic terms, as they are primarily interested in their own gain. This is said to result from ideological control of the proletariat and common laborers, something quite evident through the conditioning of people in Brave New World. The common classes, Delta, Gamma, etc., have no true will of their own; through hypnopaedia, the drive to consume, to spend, to indulge is reinforced above all else. This is manipulated, as mentioned earlier, by the World Controller. Hegemony, essentially the idea that groups of social classes are dominated entirely by a separate group of individuals, is clearly used in this case. The lower classes are completely unaware of the manipulation, quite literally 'buying into an ideology that supports this structure' (i.e., capitalism and consumerism). The upper classes are born with the ability to be aware of it but do nothing; few Alphas or Betas, beyond characters like Bernard, do much more than accept their place. In fact, the interactions of the social classes, as will be discussed more extensively, are significant indications of the perceived oppression of capitalism.

Relationships between disparate individuals do not exist in Brave New World. The novel seemingly refuses to distinguish the characters - they are, even among major characters, lacking depth. Perhaps Huxley suggests that the rise of technology and capitalism together deprives man of free will and expression. Love does not exist, nor do the extremes of any one emotion; rather, interactions are kept superficial, portrayed distinctly through the men's remarks about women, primarily about their physical appearance (i.e., pneumatic quality), and the women's unashamed comments about their encounters, so to speak. Furthermore, each societal class's complacency with their status in the hierarchy indicates the socioeconomic effect of capitalism. Their absolute obedience to their role in the community is an indication of Marxist thought on the proletariat, who are falsely assured of their own superiority over all else as long as they continue to consume, obey, and stay in line with the rest of their peers.

Almost four years ago, I took a course on Islam at CBC. One of the main topics of heated discussion was whether Islam is a hostile religion. I think this question is more relevant today than ever. Looking back on events since 9/11, I've seen mass media shift from a hostile view of Islam and extremists to extreme tolerance for Islam in America. I don't think we could have had a presidential candidate named Barack Obama, with an apparent Muslim background in his family, in 2001.

The biography of the Prophet intrigues me because, from what I know of Muhammad's history, the biography contradicts his personality. From what I've learned, I thought Muhammad forced conversions to Islam. He would conquer tribes and then force them to adopt Islam. But according to the biography, Muhammad was portrayed as a kind of martyr, misunderstood and even humbled himself before others. Then, one by one, people came to see the 'truth' in his teachings and sought him out.

There are also uncanny similarities between the ministries of Jesus and the 'miracles' of Muhammad. The most obvious is when he multiplied mutton and milk to feed more than forty men. This style of writing makes me believe the authors wanted Muhammad to be seen as a humble prophet who didn't need to prove anything, simply living in truth and miracles. This kind of fallacy is the worst because it undermines the miracles and life of Jesus Christ. To me, it's like they are trying to take credit for the life and persona of Jesus through Muhammad.

There are also many stories in the biography that make it seem like part of their agenda is to provide proof of 'witnesses' or how people 'on their own' converted to Islam. But the problem is that many stories are from at least a third-party perspective. In the story, the author illustrates that they heard from someone who heard from someone else, and so on. I didn't like this much because, although they intended to provide proof of the stories' truth, I thought it weakened them and made them seem more suspicious.

What bothers me most about this work is that they try to exalt Muhammad as a godly man who was humble, endearing, wise, and gentle. But history contradicts the idea that Muhammad was gentle and humble, and I can't help but wonder if Muslims today know the true history behind Muhammad's rise to power.

The teachings of Jesus and the beliefs he held during his life were quickly set aside as Christian thought developed after his time. Looking at this history broadly, we see Christianity drifting further from its origins. Today's world shows an increasing awareness and an unprecedented progressive trend. While traditional people remain and resist any thinking beyond what they've been taught, this group may not be influential enough to impact the whole. Among Christians, historical awareness is expected to grow significantly in the future. A desire will spread to distinguish doctrines added over time from the true intentions of the religion's founder. It may take decades or even centuries, but the outcome is inevitable: a significant reversal in the direction of Christian history. There will be a return to its original form. A growing movement will emerge, removing layers of doctrine, one by one, as if time were turning back, until only a conception of what Jesus introduced to humanity on behalf of God is left, before any other thinkers made such claims. As this trend moves through the United States and Europe, influencing masses to worship as if living in Jesus' time, following only his ideas, the church as an institution will remain strong to lead. However, as the theological clock moves backward, the extreme diversity in Christendom will shift towards more uniformity in belief and practice. Across regions, denominations, and divisions of all kinds, we'll see increasing similarities rather than differences. Human history is filled with significant reversions. One example is how Christians were once persecuted by the Roman Empire, which later became a Christian institution. Our country has moved from African-American slavery to African-American leadership. The significant reversion in our future will unfold within the Christian religion, undoing history in search of its source, and undoing diversity in the process. It's crucial to note that part of what will enable this process is interpreting Jesus' words metaphorically, rather than literally. So, what has happened since Jesus' lifetime? Looking far back into history, we find only Judaism, the theological foundation for Christianity. Monotheism, the perception of a divinely revealed religion, and the authority of the Hebrew scriptures were central by the time the Romans took control of Jerusalem in 63 B.C.E. The Jewish population did not share a single spirit; they divided into Sadducees, Pharisees, Essenes, Zealots, and a majority of common people.

I believe that "The Jungle" reveals how humans are naturally greedy and self-centered at their core. They only look out for themselves and aim to make their lives as good as possible, without consideration for those beneath them. "The Jungle" illustrates this in various ways. The most obvious aspect is the owners and managers of large factories. Their sole focus is on making their companies and factories as large and successful as they can be. They do not care about anyone or anything that obstructs their path or is harmed by their progress. According to Upton Sinclair's work: "The line of buildings stood clear and black against the sky; here and there, the great chimneys rose from the mass, with the river of smoke streaming away to the end of the world." Sinclair attempts to depict the significant damage caused by this pollution. He shows that the owners have no concern for any person or animal that might be harmed. They are indifferent to the massive plumes of smoke billowing out of the factories or the runoff of animal waste from the thousands of pens in Packingtown. The owners and managers also did not care for their employees who made them wealthy. They would do anything to earn or save an extra dollar: "From top to bottom, the place is simply a seething cauldron of jealousies and hatred; there is no loyalty or decency anywhere, no place where a man mattered against a dollar." They forced their employees to work terrible hours and could lay off multitudes of people at a moment's notice without any compensation or assistance in finding a job. During the era "The Jungle" is set, there were few, if any, laws or regulations ensuring the safety or well-being of workers. This allowed managers and owners to run unchecked, forcing their employees to accelerate progress and work under dreadful conditions. Although the book never states it directly, those who lived and worked themselves to death in Packingtown were simply expected to endure the harsh conditions both in the factories and around them. There were no agencies or organizations to provide information or assistance to the working man. Unions did exist, but they often caused more harm than good by profiting off the poor workers. The workers were treated so poorly and had no escape from the system of Packingtown, that they were described as slaves: "Here is a population, low-class and mostly foreign, always on the brink of starvation and dependent for its livelihood on the whims of men as brutal and unscrupulous as the slave drivers of old; under such circumstances, immorality is as inevitable and prevalent as under the system of chattel slavery."

Dream-Land is one of Edgar Allan Poe’s self-proclaimed better poems. In "Dream-Land," Poe uses the term "Thule" in lines 6 and 56, which Mabbott traces back to Virgil. Virgil used the term to refer to an island north of Britain that the Greeks considered the edge of the known world. While it is certain that Virgil used the term, there is a more contemporary source that deserves some credit. Poe was very interested in German authors. This quote is important because it shows Poe's familiarity with Goethe's writings. In his book Poe's Politian and Goethe's Mignon, Karl J. Arndt comments on the similarity of their two poems, concluding that Poe was imitating Goethe. The Oxford Companion to English Literature notes that Goethe was a celebrated writer of the poetic drama Faust, published in two parts, the first in 1808 and the second in the year of Goethe’s death in 1832. Within the poetic verse of the second part of Faust lies a short poem titled "The King of Thule." The poem is about a king whose wife dies after giving him the gift of a goblet. After his wife's death, he begins drinking heavily and weeping from the memory of his dead queen. He then decides it is time for him to die, and he gives his possessions to his children, except for the goblet. He walks to a cliff, throws the goblet into the sea, closes his eyes, and dies. The demeanor of the King of Thule and the description of the king in Dream-Land are very similar, perhaps a dark double of Poe's loss and drinking habits. Faust was also adapted into a romantic drama by H P Grattan in 1842, less than a year before Poe used the term Thule in "The Pit and the Pendulum." Poe references Thule twice in his collected writings. Once, he mentions "ultma Thule" in The Pit and the Pendulum, but he uses this phrase twice in "Dream-Land" as bookends for the poem. "The King of Thule" and "Dream-Land" can be read as companion pieces. In "Dream-Land," the speaker describes the landscape of Thule as dark and lonely, haunted by dead friends, and sees a shadowy world without color. All these scenes would be read into "The King of Thule" by Goethe, as he has just lost his wife, is lonely, and has lost his will to rule or even live. The entire poem is described as if the speaker had stepped into Goethe's poem. Goethe was a significant author whom Poe would have known, if for no other reason than his respect for Tennyson. Poe had this to say when asked if he admired Tennyson. Apart from the connection to Tennyson, Poe would have been exposed to Goethe's work in the many reproductions that took place after the original publication.

Under California law, a customer who was injured after slipping and falling on an applesauce spill in a grocery store could potentially be awarded punitive damages by demonstrating that the store manager acted with malice. This could be shown if the manager was informed twice about the spill and failed to have it cleaned for half an hour because he was having dinner. A judge is unlikely to summarily dismiss Jennifer Palmer's claim for punitive damages. To substantiate such a claim, the plaintiff must provide evidence that the defendant's actions were committed with a willful and conscious disregard for the likely harm that would result from the conduct, and that the actions were despicable. Palmer can argue that Martin should have been aware of the probable harm of not cleaning up a spill, as several D&D customers had been injured from slipping in the months before her accident. Despite this knowledge, he still failed to have the spill cleaned. Palmer's argument that Martin's actions were despicable is less convincing but still reasonable given that six slip-and-fall incidents occurred in 2009 and Martin still failed to take proper actions to ensure the safety of his store. On October 13, 2009, at 5:00 PM, Rich Wayne, an employee of D&D Markets, informed his manager, Paul Martin, about an applesauce spill in an aisle. Martin told Wayne he was on his dinner break and "didn't have time to deal with customer complaints." At 5:15 PM, another employee, Mary J. Haddigan, also notified Mr. Martin of the spill, and Martin responded in the same manner. At 5:30 PM, on the thirteenth, the plaintiff, Jennifer Palmer, slipped and fell on the spill and sustained a serious back injury. Before Palmer's accident, five different slip-and-fall incidents had been reported at D&D in 2009. Palmer is now suing D&D for compensatory and punitive damages related to her injury, and we are considering whether to file a motion for partial summary judgment against the claim for punitive damages. In California, a plaintiff can recover punitive damages for a breach of an obligation not arising from a contract if the defendant acted with "oppression, fraud, or malice." Cal. Civ. Code, § 3294(a) (Lexis 2010). The statute defines malice as conduct intended to cause harm, or absent intent, the conduct must be "despicable" and committed with "a willful and conscious disregard of the rights or safety of others." id. at § (c)(1). Courts have characterized conduct as malicious when committed with a conscious disregard for the plaintiff's rights when the defendant "was aware of the probable dangerous consequences of his conduct, and he willfully and deliberately failed to avoid those consequences." Taylor v. Super. Ct. of Los Angeles Co., 598 P. 2d 853, 856 (Cal. 1979).

She had always felt like something was missing. It was this desire that could not be fulfilled. It began when she was about 14 years old, just entering teenage life. And it was still there three years later, at the age of 17. By now, she realized she wanted someone rather than something. Yet, she felt no interest in boys. Some were attracted to her and went through awkward attempts to woo the uncharmable, but no one appealed to her. She often questioned herself with this strange feeling, trying to figure out what could cause such an odd thing in a teenage girl. The few years of reflection had brought up theories, but nothing substantial enough to truly consider. So she continued living, constantly questioning her desires.

A day at home was usually peaceful. Her parents were good and calm people. They never argued with each other, and oddly enough, arguments with their daughter were rare too. The only thing they ever argued about was her asserting her independence and free personality. She was the daughter of a very calm couple, yet she definitely countered their energies with her vibrant and fun personality, which made her very likable along with the fact that she was a nice person.

Today, however, was not a calm day. As she moved from room to room, trying to find new inspiration for herself, she heard a short scream from the kitchen, the sound of her mother's beautiful voice. She ran into the room, starting to panic as she frantically asked, "Mom?! Mom, what's wrong?!" She saw her mother lying on the floor, appearing to be in pain as she kept saying "Ow" in short breaths. The mother's daughter ran to her side and put a hand on her to try to help. "Ouch ... sweetie, I ... need you to take me - to the hospital." The words were rushed and strained, and her daughter could tell she was in immense pain. "Okay Mom, just tell me where I can pick you up." Her mother gestured with her hands, and at that moment, the hero of the house was very grateful she had taken classes to strengthen herself. She carried her mother to the car, laid her in the back lying down, and drove off.

A visit to the hospital brought the smell of disinfectant and illness, laced with fear. But she wasn't sensing that, as her mind was too occupied with helping her mother. She quickly carried the injured woman in and started calling for help from the doctors. A few worried faces gathered around, and someone quickly pulled up a rolling bed and laid her mother down on it. They took her for immediate examination, and her daughter was left to sit in worry.

Her mother had fallen from a stepping stool while trying to retrieve a vase from the highest cabinet they had.

The aim of this study was to demonstrate that adherence to a "Mediterranean Diet" (Med diet), as indicated by a high "alternative Mediterranean (aMed) diet score," is linked to a reduced risk of chronic heart disease (CHD) and stroke, as well as mortality from stroke. The aMed diet is a modified form of the Med diet, featuring greater consumption of plant-based foods, including plant proteins (excluding potatoes but including fruits, nuts, whole grains, and legumes), monounsaturated fats (as opposed to saturated fats), and fish, with lower consumption of animal products and saturated fats. Moderate alcohol consumption is permitted.

Previous prospective studies documented an inverse relationship between adherence to a Med diet and the risk of overall and cardiovascular (CVD) mortality, and an intervention trial demonstrated that the Med diet was more effective than a low-fat diet in promoting weight loss and reducing the ratio of total to high-density lipoprotein cholesterol in obese individuals. Earlier studies did not focus on stroke or mortality from stroke.

This epidemiological study tracked 74,886 women, aged 38 to 63, without a history of CVD or diabetes, who are participants in the Nurses' Health Study, a cohort study of 121,700 female nurses from 11 US states. From 1984 to 2004, the authors calculated an aMed diet score six times using self-reported "food frequency questionnaires" (FFQs) designed to assess nutrient intake over the previous year. Over 95% of nurses remained in the study throughout the 20-year period. The FFQs were subjected to validation studies. Reports of CHD, fatal CHD, and stroke were confirmed by reviewing medical or hospital records, autopsies, or death certificates. Where records were lacking, cases were classified as "probable" and included, with about 17% of all strokes and 24% of nonfatal myocardial infarctions categorized in this way. Body mass index, smoking status, aspirin use, multivitamin intake, menopausal status, and use of postmenopausal hormones were calculated for each FFQ, and from 1986, leisure-time physical activity was evaluated.

To reduce random variation for individuals and better represent long-term dietary intake, cumulative averages of the aMed score from the repeated FFQs were calculated (averaging scores from two prior years). Adjustments were made for "confounders" (factors that could skew results) by adjusting for age, smoking, BMI, menopausal status, postmenopausal hormone use, multivitamin intake, alcohol intake, physical activity, and aspirin use.

Cox proportional-hazard modeling was used to analyze the association between an aMed score and the risk of CHD and stroke, using separate models for fatal and nonfatal CHD and stroke types.

Higher adherence to the Mediterranean diet, as indicated by a higher aMed diet score, was associated with a reduced risk of developing CHD and stroke in women. During the 20-year follow-up, there were 2391 incident cases of CHD, 1763 incident cases of stroke, and 1077 cardiovascular disease deaths (including both fatal CHD and strokes). Women in the top aMed quintile were at a lower risk for both CHD and stroke compared to those in the bottom quintile (relative risk [RR], 0.71).

The sign says, Hitler is alive in Burma.

Ellen Page, the star of Juno, stands alone on a street corner holding a piece of cardboard above her head, with the disturbing message written in marker on her sign. Burma, also known as Myanmar, is a Southeast Asian country ruled by a tyrannical military junta that came to power in 1962 through a coup. In 2007, numerous street protests took place, the first public demonstrations in a decade. Led by a large number of Burmese monks, these protests were named the "Saffron Revolution," after the color of the robes worn by the monks. After the initial uprisings, the general public began taking an interest in the protests, and although the Burmese government initially grudgingly allowed the monks to hold peaceful gatherings, the violence soon escalated into what some considered an all-out war between the monks and the military junta, with the military actively invading and looting monasteries across the country. Foreign journalists were arrested on sight, and a Japanese photojournalist named Kenji Nagai was killed on September 27, 2007, simply for attending a street protest. While the official death toll is 13, Colonel Hla Win, who defected from the army a few days before the official report, was quoted saying, "Many more people have been killed in recent days than you've heard about. The bodies can be counted in several thousand."

This is nothing new. While these are some of the most recent examples of atrocities occurring in our world, a government's desire to suppress dissent and maintain complete control over its citizens has existed as long as civilization itself. Early Roman emperors declared themselves chosen by the gods to have complete executive rule over every aspect of their society. Japanese emperors are believed to actually be gods, sent to our world to lead their people to prosperity through the invention of Motorola cell phones and hara-kiri, and our current president, George W. Bush, has weekly conference calls with Ted Haggard, the leader of Stupid People Worldwide, a subsidiary group of the Republican Party.

Some of the best-known examples of such actions include incidents like the June 4, 1989 protest at Tiananmen Square, where intellectuals, labor activists, and students gathered to protest the authoritarian rule of the government. The death toll in that instance varies widely, with official reports from the Chinese government stating 200-300 dead, while the Chinese Red Cross reports between 2,000-3,000 dead. Another is the Rwandan genocide of the 1990s, where Hutu militia groups, aided by the Rwandan government, began a systematic killing of all Tutsis, as well as political moderates, irrespective of their ethnic backgrounds. Hitler's 'Third Reich,' a period spanning several years and numerous countries where anyone of Jewish descent was rounded up and killed, is another extreme example.

Duke Ellington's impact on jazz is largely attributed to his long career and his creative talent in shaping his orchestra. While Ellington's presence at the piano is subtle in many compositions chosen for this assignment, as a composer, he excelled in crafting rich and complex pieces that highlighted the individual talents of his band members. He created frameworks that allowed soloists to improvise freely, in addition to composing tightly orchestrated pieces and phrases that utilized the distinctive styles of band members to emphasize musical ideas. In doing so, he also accentuated the overall tone of the orchestra, creating coherent and original sounds tailored to each piece. Ellington's mastery of the sound of individual players and their integration into a growing ensemble enabled him to write some of the most innovative and brilliant pieces in jazz history.

The Grove Music dictionary, when discussing Ellington's sound and innovation, references "Creole Love Call" in relation to his use of voice "as a jazz instrument" throughout his career. This is an early example of Ellington's use of voice to add texture and color, unencumbered by lyrics. "Creole Love Call" also demonstrates Ellington's ability to complement the style of his soloists, a skill evident throughout his career. This slow, deliberate twelve-bar blues piece comprises six choruses, as follows:

Chorus 1: Call and response between voice and reeds, where the voice starts smooth and melodic, transitioning to a rougher sound towards the end.
Chorus 2: Muted trumpet solo that elaborates on the basic melody and emphasizes extended blue notes.
Chorus 3: Sweeping clarinet solo in a high register, accompanied by a subtle syncopated piano phrase.
Chorus 4: Full band echoes the first chorus with a call and response between brass and reed sections.
Chorus 5: The climactic chorus, as reeds initiate the call and response in a high register, backed by syncopated stop-time from the brass and rhythm sections.
Chorus 6: Returns to the structure of the first chorus, with call and response between voice and reeds. In this chorus, the voice adopts the "growl" technique, soloing as an instrument.
Tag: A brief tag featuring a vocal run and a dissonant novelty ending by a trombone.

Ellington's use of voice to add a tonal dimension to this piece exemplifies a stylistic trait prevalent throughout his work.

In "Hot and Bothered," recorded a year later, Ellington combines his skill for tight orchestration with his ear for tone color. A call and response between "Bubber" Miley on muted trumpet and Baby Cox’s scat singing utilizes the vocal aspects of Miley's playing and the instrumental qualities of Cox's voice to create a rich and complementary sound. "It Don’t Mean a Thing (If It Ain’t Got That Swing)" furthers these ideas, as Ellington employs Joe "Tricky Sam" Nanton, a staple in Ellington's orchestra, to great effect in introducing the melody with a muted trombone.

Why do organisms evolve in the way that they do? Are there limitations or constraints that influence the direction of evolutionary change? Although D’Arcy Thompson remarked in 1917 that “Even now the zoologist has scarce begun to dream of defining in mathematical language even the simplest organic forms,” this still holds true today. Recently, mathematical modeling has been applied to general aspects of mollusk skeletogenesis through both ontogeny and phylogeny (e.g., Raup and Stanley, 1981). Our study explores how mathematical modeling of ontogenetic and phylogenetic changes in Prunum, combined with experimental studies, can be used to clarify the mechanisms involved in the direction and magnitude of evolutionary-developmental changes. We used X-ray images of Prunum species to define quantitative parameters that could, in turn, be used to model hypothetical and actual skeletal morphologies. These parameters were entered into the software program CerioShell (Stone, 1995). We modeled hypothetical shell morphologies that could help interpret the boundaries of possible morphological change in Prunum. These results are being combined with experimental and descriptive studies to better understand macroevolutionary events in this clade.

A shell can be considered a structure like a tube traveling over time through 360 degrees of space. These revolutions or turns of a coiled shell are called whorls, which spiral around an imaginary central axis. This axis runs through the central column of the shell and is known as the columella. The rate at which the whorls enlarge can vary, and a continuous line separates each whorl, known as a suture. In most shells, the largest whorl is the last whorl (body whorl). The spire is considered all the whorls except the last one. The apex is the tip of the spire, and the opposite end is referred to as the base. The animal extends out of its shell through an opening called the aperture.

Shells can be viewed in apical, basal, apertural, and abapertural views. (The "usual" orientation of a shell is an apertural view, with the aperture facing the viewer and the apex pointing upwards.)

A method for counting whorls is described below. First, the shell should be viewed from the apical perspective, and then it should be determined where the first suture begins. A line can then be drawn to divide the shell into two parts. Whorls are counted from this line and estimated to a quarter of a whorl.

A shell can be seen as a series of apertures that travel through time and space as the animal builds its shell. It is possible to trace the path of the aperture via the coordinates of the center of each whorl’s aperture, as well as the horizontal and vertical radius of the aperture.

This trajectory can be graphically and mathematically represented. Once a mathematical formulation is established, it is possible to vary parameters and modify the mollusk’s skeletogenesis.

The rate of neonatal and infant mortality in Indonesia has remained fairly stable over the last ten years. While the country is on track to achieve many of the Millennium Development Goals, such as those for water and sanitation, the rates of improvement in child and maternal health are woefully inadequate to meet the targets by 2015. The multiple reasons for these shortcomings are discussed below, highlighting the need to strengthen the health system rather than focus on program-specific interventions.
